  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3169393266" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3169393266" />
    <a title="Kyra Leseberg (Roots &amp; Reads)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5899398-kyra-leseberg-roots-reads"><img alt="Kyra Leseberg (Roots &amp; Reads)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1523718393p2/5899398.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3169393266?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kyra Leseberg (Roots &amp; Reads)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kyra Leseberg (Roots &amp; Reads)" href="/user/show/5899398-kyra-leseberg-roots-reads">Kyra Leseberg (Roots &amp; Reads)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3169393266" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9703278222357596798">3.5 stars<br/><br/>Harry Crane is an old man now with plenty of time to reflect on the past.  What he remembers most vividly is his childhood in Marvel Creek, Texas.<br/><br/>In 1933, Harry was 11 years old.  He spent most of his time roaming the woods with his younger sister Tom (short for Thomasina) and their faithful dog Toby.  Their father is the local constable who also farms and owns the town barbershop and their mama is a kind and beautiful woman treated as an equal by her husband (a rarity in that era).<br/><br/>Thei</span>
  <span id="freeText9703278222357596798" style="display:none">3.5 stars<br /><br />Harry Crane is an old man now with plenty of time to reflect on the past.  What he remembers most vividly is his childhood in Marvel Creek, Texas.<br /><br />In 1933, Harry was 11 years old.  He spent most of his time roaming the woods with his younger sister Tom (short for Thomasina) and their faithful dog Toby.  Their father is the local constable who also farms and owns the town barbershop and their mama is a kind and beautiful woman treated as an equal by her husband (a rarity in that era).<br /><br />Their lives change dramatically on the evening Harry and Tom venture too far into the woods and discover the mutilated body of a woman.<br /><br />Harry's father, Jacob, is determined to identify the woman and locate her killer but the white population of Marvel Creek isn't too worried about the death of a black woman.  When the body of another woman is discovered, only then does the town begin to worry about a looming threat to white women.<br /><br />Jacob's investigation creates a stir in the segregated community and sets in motion a series of events that will change the small town forever.<br /><br />An old black man named Mose is questioned when circumstancial evidence is discovered.  Though Mose is released, a crowd gathers to be both judge and jury.  Harry and Jacob are unable to save Mose from a (<i>*warning: graphic*</i>) brutal lynching.<br /><br />When months pass without the discover of another body, the town is lulled into a sense of safety and belief they've taken care of the threat.<br />But the killer is still among them... and now Tom is in danger.<br /><br />I don't want to give too much away!  Harry's narration offers comfort in this dark story as he shares his innocent childhood thoughts and perspectives with the added insight he has gained over his lifetime.<br /><br /><b>The Bottoms</b> is a horror story about a serial killer on the loose in a small town but it's also a horror story about the town itself.  Racism runs rampant in Marvel Creek and the threat of the KKK and lynch mob mentality is just as dangerous as the killer preying on local women.<br /><br />There are several similarities between <b>The Bottoms</b> and <b>To Kill a Mockingbird</b>.  Jacob is very much like Atticus Finch in his fight for fairness and justice.  Harry and Tom mirror Jem and Scout in personality.  The authors both use adult narrators sharing childhood memories.  <b>TKAM</b> had the mystery of Boo Radley, <b>The Bottoms</b> has the mystery of The Goat Man. Both are set in small Southern towns and center around a violent crime with a black man unjustly accused.<br /><br />All of that said, <b>The Bottoms</b> stands on its own.  It's horrific and graphic in several instances while managing moments of beauty and nostalgia interspersed with humor, thanks to the innocence of childhood. <br /><br />I recommend <b>The Bottoms</b> to readers who enjoy historical fiction, horror, and mystery/crime.<br /><br />For more reviews, visit <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.rootsandreads.wordpress.com">www.rootsandreads.wordpress.com</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="9703278222357596798" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


